een so captivated by a title more than this one.Everybody at least needs to try the demo. Not too hard to pick up and get in to the flow of things.I hope stuff like colonies,factions and races come to this game.I believe this could be one of the greatest games ever made. Hands down.If I was a multi-millionaire, I would so back this Dev on this game. You have a rare jewel here and I hope nothing as trivial as money stops this game from becoming what it has to be.I know this was kind of an abnormal review, more like praise, but I do not care.GET IT GET IT GET IT....................................................................................."
76561198021354223,Recommended,314230,32412724,Posted: 14 June,all,Doctor 7-93D,"Now I won't usually review early access games, this will probably be the only one, I also apologize for my poor grammar.Now since that is out of the way let's get on with the review.Rodina is a space exploration game that currently is barebones in terms of content but is being worked on by a very kind and surprisingly responsive developer. The core game it's self right now is as follows.GAMEPLAYThe gameplay in Rodina Is, as of now, mediocre for a space game. You can land on asteroids and planets, or burn up like I did and be amazed by the pretty sights, go in space battles or combat in fps style. You may also salvage data sticks and other supplies. The data sticks are these little bits of the story and surprisingly funny. That's about it, not much, but there may be much more according to raptor (The dev)In terms of bugs there aren't many due to the lack of content, as the game is currently a frame for what's to come. But there is a surprising amount of freedom in customization of your vessel (interior only),and that freedom will only improve as I see.Space combat is surprisingly good, much better then others as the fire mechanic can lead to some pretty intense battles with multiple craft, really makes you have to use some maneuvers to avoid missiles and blasters, but even this can get repetitive at times.Another big aspect of the game is customizing your ship, many of my hours in the game have been customizing trying new layouts as there is simply so much you can do and it'll only get better with time.Another plus the game gets is the lack of loading screens, as this is much better for people who love immersion in their games. There isn t even a loading screen on new game. Speaking of which, The beginning of the game is pretty simple, you spawn on  an asteroid near your ship, after a basic tutorial you get in and from there salvage and fight. That's basically the whole game for now.STORYBelieve it or not the story for this game is very interesting and original (compared to the other space games) and the game currently tells the story through data sticks you find, the story from what I put together goes as: Humanity has grown tired and used up earth, now boarding a massive scale ship, called the Rodina is heading towards a star system called the Zorica system, housing 4 planets and an asteroid belt, now your character who by default is named Sara was aboard a space craft sent to colonize the system, prior to the Rodina.The Zorica system was infested with aliens who destroyed the vanguard and your the only know survivor, your only goal right now is kill as many aliens, possibly wiping them our or driving them out so they don't destroy all of humanity when the Rodina arrives.So the story is very original and the story telling as well is fun!GRAPHICSThe graphics in Rodina have a cute little pixels in them and a nice charm to them, specifically the fire extinguisher affects after putting out a fire. I'm sure there will be many improvements and changes. Its very easy to run and you should be fine running it.AUDIOThe sounds in the game are cute and fun, while the music is simply spectacular, If you want to help Raptor make this game then go ahead and buy the soundtrack as it has a very ominous and star trek feel to it, winning me over instantly.OVERALLOverall Rodina in its current state, can be fun at times but might not be a game you'll play all day, not yet already as it's currently lacking in content but that's soon to change and I have great faith in Raptor for making this good game and if you want to support it too, go buy it as the price range is fair for its current state as well.6/10A good game that's above average at the moment, I'm sure that will change for the better."
76561198045472900,Recommended,314230,28134481,"Posted: 2 December, 2016",all,orgaya38,"What is more frightening than a God?This question was posed to me upon completing Rodina's main story, as well as the answer, in quick succession.  Not literally, of course, but thematically; I felt that this was the underlying thesis of the entire work.  My interpretation, anyway.That's probably a pretentious way to start.  Okay!  I'll talk about the game now in more literal terms.Short version:Do I recommend?  That depends.  Rodina is quickly becoming one of my favorite games, but that's because it's both a fun  activity that revolves around interesting exploration in a vast, vast world and a vehicle for philosophical quandaring through some pretty excellent writing.  If this does not appeal to you, then no, I don't recommend.  If it sounds remotely intriguing, then yes, I whole-heartedly recommend.  Do it.  Play the demo.  Then pay the 250 that this company sorely deserves (if I had that on hand I would do so in a heart-beat).Long version:I'll describe the game by listing and explaining each facet any game would typically have.Graphics:Subpar.  I find the visuals to be charming, reminding me of a few games I used to play when I was a kid fiddling around with my parents' bulky Macintosh.  Honestly I never cared about the graphical style of a game I'm playing, so long as it doesn't hamper the overall experience (I like Minecraft, for example).  Compared to some AAA games out there, it'd get trampled in this department.  However, I think the initially unappealing look of the game works to the game's advantage, in what I think the game attempts to portray.  I won't spoil, however.(I saw that there was a separate artist for this game, so don't take this as me dissing you - I'm only comparing it to games that have like a zillion dollars backing it and pretty much nothing else, and also I can barely draw a stick figure so take that what its worth.)Gameplay:The actual, full-on, no BS reason I bought this game in the first place was because I read you can walk around in your own ship.  Seriously.  After playing Starbound and finding great satisfaction in essentially piloting a flying house, not being tethered to anything anywhere else, I was greeted with a great sense of freedom I don't find in any other game.  Alas, Starbound was still limited (2D notwithstanding), and I longed for even greater freedom.  Rodina, then, heard my call, burst into my living room, stripped itself of all clothing articles, and demanded that I make love with it.  Of course with the graphics I was mostly aversive but I at least complimented its hair.Okay, okay.  So yes.  Walking around in your own ship - a ship whose interior you can design AND walk around in whilst mid-flight - was just really fun for me.  As was the difficult control scheme.  Learning to fly took a lot of effort, but it made it worth it.  Same with dog-fighting.  I've seen complaints for this, but honestly, I found the hectic nature of the space battles riveting.  Especially when you're in the atmosphere of a planet, having to pay attention to where you are so you don't burn up while also keeping track of the swarm of enemies trying to practice their anti-protagonist agenda.In addition to movement and such, I am also continuously amazed at the size of this world.  It's merely a solar system, yes, but holy cow is it gigantic.  The planets feel collosal, in a way that makes you quickly realize that you're just a speck.  Likewise with the distance between planets and asteroids.  There's just a scope here that I'm still wrapping my head around.  If nothing else, this game seriously hammers in the idea that, hey, space is really big.  Like, bigger than the biggest thing you can think of.  Yes, THAT big.  Some kind of space scientist would be proud.If I had one minor complaint, though, it's that I think the Xenos' weapons are a bit over-powered.  Not against your character, mind - that's just fine.  I expect a rocket to blow your face off.  However, how come a few pew pew bullets can down your entire space-craft?  Especially those homing thingies.  Two of those and you're gone.  Feels kind of uneven to me, but what do I know?Story:And this is where we rub up on the reason I think this game works as well as it does.  I'll get this out of the way, first, though - the writing is excellent.  Delegated to out-of-the-way documents that you can collect, each contain a small part of a short story that interconnects with the greater context of the universe.  It is not required that you read any of them in order to get any enjoyment out of the game, but doing so will deepen the world you inhabit while you murder those poor green men.That is, until you rip through the story without reading anything and get to the end, where you should be thoroughly confused by what happens.  And this is where I fell in love with the game.It's not visibly enormous or spectacular by any means, no.  It'd just generate a small bit of confusion that may compel you to read why it happened.  But for me, this created a thrust that I just haven't seen anywhere else.  A context was created that perfectly married the graphics, game, and story into a single entity - you.  The player.  A trajectory is set at that moment, one that I'm unsure could be stopped, and I think the understanding of that is what propels this game into the profound.  In the end, it made me realize that with the scope of the game's world, the abilities I possessed, and the enemies I've mowed down, I realized what exactly this protagonist was capable of now, and will be capable of in the future.The game at this point asks, what is more frightening than a God?  And you get the answer to that as quick as the question is asked.  And this, Mr. Ebert, is why you're wrong - this video game IS art, and it's art in a way that no other form of media would be able to accomplish.  Or I could just be talking out of my♥♥♥♥♥like some pretentious hipster.Anyway, to all those involved in this wonderful work's creation, thank you."
