76561197969847656,Recommended,314230,31583336,Posted: 6 May,all,Hell_MINTH,"This game is phenomenal.  Absolutely fantastic!  It's built in an old-school style, with no loading screens, no waypoints, no tutorials, no dumbed down guidance.  It gives (nearly) absolute freedom to go whereever you want, do whatever you want (aside from a minor planet-locking system, which is not grindy and well-done IMHO).  The game plays completely in first person, or allows you to move about in your ship first person and fly third person (I personally prefer all first-person play).  You literally press a button, while flying, and can walk about your ship as you fly, totally seamless.  You can open your airlock (while in space) and get sucked out as the interior atmosphere escapes into space, you can jump out of your ship while planetside and drop to the planet.  Atmospheric re-entry is extremly cool, and gives you the feeling that you are in a real spaceship being tossed, turned, and burned as you plunge.Gameplay mechanics perfectly follow the KISS (keep it simple stupid) principle, there are debris fields all over the asteroid belt and the four planets, which are inhabited by Xenos (hostile aliens) who attack you from various ships, and also on the ground in a sort of ""Tribes"" like FPS combat.  As you gather debris and encryption keys from the debris fields, more of the story unlocks (all text based).  Don't be dissuaded by the text based story, it is extremely well written and pulls you into the game like a good book, and has a fantastic twist.Probably the very best aspect is the musical soundtrack.  It flawlessly captures the feeling of lonesome space sickness, the awe of extra-solar planetary exploration, and changes thematically depending upon your position, with each planet and area getting it's own theme.  The music is in an orchestral style, and holds it's own against the likes of John Williams (Star Wars).Can't wait to see where this developer takes Rodina next.  Speaking as an older old-school gamer, this game is absolutely the best thing to happen to space games since LucasFilms in the late eighties.All that said, if you are a multiplayer fan (I am not), I don't know that this would be the title for you, as I don't believe the developer has worked on netcode or has any plans to incorporate it (fairly certain here).  Also, there is no voice acting, and no top-of the line animations, though what is there (animation wise) is extremely smooth and aesthetically pleasing in it's own right.  Also, while the planets and planetside landings are extremely cool, and the seamless nature of the game makes them fun to explore, they are rather barren, and could use quite a bit of love.Can't recommend this one enough, it stands with the best classics."
