,Recommended,314230,32054231,Posted: 29 May,all,Badgerspin,"Damn good game with a hell of a lot of potential. The dev posts updates regularly and is active in communicating where the game is going, so this is one piece of early access that I have no worries about becoming abandonware.The story, while complete as far as major plot elements, is still unfinished. Mind you, the story itself is entirely text based, but it's damn well written. They did a great job of keeping me both guessing and wanting more. I found myself trying to bolt from place to place to find out how everything would progress.Exploration is definitely this game's strongest point. The planets are HUGE and there's plenty to poke around with in the asteroid belt. There are some elements that haven't been finished yet, but that you can find floating in orbit within the system. To say that I'm curious to see how they're going to be implimented would be an understatement.Some elements do feel somewhat grind-y. The big one being ground combat with collecting items. I like curve-balls thrown my way with games like this, so take what I say next as you will. When landing to collect items, there's always a handful of ground troops to deal with. While that's not a bad thing, there's not really much variation with it. (Especially with the variety and number of enemies you come up against.) Sure, you could land, get out of your ship, and engage them that way, but over time I found myself just hovering above them in my starship lighting them up with the ship's main guns. The situation felt a little... Overpowered. (Though there was one instance where a ground troop had some sort of rocket launcher energy weapon that wrecked my shizzle. Pleasant surprise and I appreciated having to mix up my strategy.) I have nothing wrong with a situation like that, but being able to rinse-later-repeat that scenario over and over again feels like a bit of a balancing issue to me. If they added some element that necessitated me getting out of my ship to attack the enemy, that would help mix things up a bit. Maybe add something like SAM/AA batteries (Both stationary and mobile) that can fire at you while in the ship, but not on the ground. Another idea would be to have the enemy send out something like a distress call to nearby patrolling aircraft if you're attacking the ground forces with your ship rather than on foot. There are some aircraft patrols, but they're not very regular. The potential is definitely there, but there's certainly room for improvement.Aircraft battles, by comparison, are significantly more difficult and far more satisfying when you win. (Ground battles are definitely lacking in the satisfaction/accomplishment department even when you're fighting from the ground.) Strangely, the battleships are fairly easy to take out with a hit and run tactic, while bombers with fighter escorts are way harder to deal with. (Enjoyably so too.)Overall, this game is definitely worth the price. (I have yet to run into any noticeable bugs. The whole thing runs really smooth.) It's immensely enjoyable. Normally I try to stay away from early access, but this one is truly a gem. Awesome as it is in its current state, I'm definitely looking forward to future updates."
76561197989683828,Recommended,314230,23028035,"Posted: 16 May, 2016",all,Cristovelli,"Took a couple of hours of play to really sink in, but Rodina even in its current form is one of my all-time favorite gaming experiences.Very immersive space exploration game with realistic planetary and solar scale. The graphics appear to be very plain and flat from the screenshots, but the beautiful lighting and atmospheric effects combine to provide breathtaking scenery, underscored by an unexpectedly powerful soundtrack of orchestral and synth space music which makes simply orbiting at speed above a planet feel profoundly emotional.The game is rather simple to play, and does a good job of leading you from quest to quest. The story presented so far at this stage of development is impressively thought-provoking and engaging, a legit science fiction epic inpsired by masters such as Azimov, Clarke and Kurzweil, with surprises for the player that deserve not to be spoiled.The controls are direct and unencumbered by over-simulation, and allow you to pilot you ship with full 6 degrees of freedom and utilize your momentum to perform satisfying maneuvers. Usually control setup and familiarization is the biggest hurdle to getting into a 3D spaceflight game, however Rodina's controls and GUI are extremely accessible, arcade-like even.An interesting feature is the various ""gears"" you can put your ship in to control speed: a slow speed for landing, a faster speed for combat, full cruising speed at which you cannot use weapons, and ultimately a giddy and scale-accurate lightspeed where the distance between objects in light-seconds is the precise amount of time it takes you to get there. Each speed setting is essentially an order of magnitude faster than the last. This system works very well to permit easy transition between the fine control needed for negotiating a landing and the coarse adjustments needed for interplanetary travel, as well as getting the hell outta Dodge when necessary.Unlilke many starfighter games, the ship does not pilot exactly like a fighter plane, but much more like the agile ship from the Descent games, and so combat can be approached with lateral strafing and reverse-thrust distancing against smaller, faster enemies, while larger, slower enemies are best circled and then rushed from the side. You can also switch to the fastest cruising speed momentarily to outrun missile locks and enemy aim, swing around and attack from the flank. The combat is solid, although more enemy ship types such as huge battleships would be nice down the line.Currently there is only ship-to-ship battle, although it appears that personal combat and invasion of enemy ships and bases is the next significant addition slated, which will certainly add new depth.There are several weapons you can acquire to fill out your ship's arsenal, from fire-and-forget missiles and bullet swarms to slow, heavy-hitting cannons. Nothing terribly incredible but a quite adequate variety to handle the 4 or 5 enemy types I've found, from light to heavy armor, each specializing in equivalent weapons to those you obtain.The story is rather short currently, I completed the main questline in a day in which I found myself incrementally engrossed in the adventure with each upgrade and story log, but I was completely satisfied with what I was able to play, and am eagerly looking forward to the additional content laid out in the development roadmap.There are many things that Rodina is not, at least currently. It is not a space trading game, or survival game, or simulation game, or a relentless high-action shooter. It is a very relaxing exploration adventure that lets you tackle the mystery of the Zorica star system at your own pace and contains all the necessary elements to make it worth the trip."
