,Recommended,314230,25024097,"Posted: 19 August, 2016",all,vaustein,"Rodina is No Man's Sky with heart.At is core, Rodina is a space-faring scavenger hunt. Although there is plenty of space fighter combat - and the AI pilots display impressive teamwork - these sequences are merely obstacles to the core of Rodina: Scouring the solar system for apocalyptic logs that tell the story of the original Rodina mission. It's clear that the developer (one person, I believe) puts most of the focus on collecting the log fragments and encrypted messages that unveil the fascinating retrospective exposition. If you enjoy reading the messages and log entries scattered throughout games like System Shock 2, Deus Ex, and Bioshock, you will find much to enjoy here.It's equally clear that combat and logistics have been super-simplified in order to prevent player frustration and to keep the focus on exploring and searching. All action takes place within a single solar system. Logistics are utterly simple: Ship and personnel damage are repaired automatically, most weapons can be fired constantly without reloading, and engine upgrades speed travel from point to point. Your ship's floor plan can be customized from the airlock menu, but this seems like a placeholder feature with no practical impact. Similarly, if a fire breaks out on your ship, you must exit the cockpit and race around the ship's deck spraying a fire extinguisher at the flames. This adds to the tension of an already dangerous battle or planetfall, but it also comes across as a placeholder with zero narrative or gameplay purpose.If Rodina truly is completely the work of a single person, that person is both a skilled software developer and a talented author of fiction. Be warned, though: If you buy Rodina as a space combat simulator in the vein of Descent: Freespace or Wing Commander, or if you don't like to read, you will be disappointed.Special praise for the soundtrack, which sets the mood perfectly even during combat."
