,Recommended,314230,11802304,"Posted: 20 August, 2014",all,K!netic,"I came to this game expecting to judge it against No Man's Sky - I've been waiting for a seamless space navigation game for a while, and NMS was the best offering I had seen. After playing Rodina, I'm certain I'll be judging NMS by how well it stacks up to Rodina.The combat is straightforward, but fresh. It doesn't feel like Freelancer or EVE or any other space game, it prioritizes momentum and special weapons. It seems to hinge on the ""stickshift"" mechanic, which works excellent with the flow of the combat/navigation, and ties everything together well. The places you visit are varied enough, but will definitely feel flat and boring after a few hours of seeing the same crevasses, blank textures, and lack of surface features save for a heightmap.Building your ship is also rewarding. After I realized that the ship was definitely bigger on the inside than it was on the outside, I decided to fix that. I'd spent too much time getting lost in the default ship anyway. In about five minutes I had a sleek interior that was sized approximately to the actual size of the ship, and looked fine. Maybe a bit bland, but the editor controls are decent enough. I could recognize some amateur tile-and-entity selection/manipulation mechanics, but with a little ironing out I'm sure it'll be fine.That makes the game sound pretty lame, I know. It's early access, and seems to be progressing apace. But what really sold me was the story.Look, I'm not one to hype up story-games, especially not when it's done in a ""find game item, read blurb, find game item, read blurb"" format like this. But my mild interest in the story turned to appreciation near the end (no spoilers), which tied together the reason you (the player) existed, why you were different, and what was going on. Very rarely do I feel like a story explains why the player acts how he does (players are crazy, we don't act at all like normal people in the real world), or why he knows nothing about the universe that everyone else has been living in. Rodina explained all of that beautifully with one single twist, and I'll recommend the game if for no other reason than to encourage someone to have that ""whoa, cool!"" moment that I didMy biggest gripe is that the re-entry mechanics are a little frustrating, and seem to take too much time with you just spinning around in place. In cruise mode in space, you can orbit any planet in under a minute, why does re-entry take so much fkn time? Why is my cruise velocity so low once I'm in atmo? I get that spaceflight would really be like this (especially in denser atmospheres), but game mechanics need to serve the game, not reality. If it wastes my time and makes me feel tied down, it shouldn't be in a free-roaming game."
