76561198201283305,Not Recommended,314230,24361357,"Posted: 16 July, 2016",all,jj,"I bought the game to support indie developing, but there wasn't for me more than 40-50 minutes of gameplay before I got tired of landing on a planet, picking up the bits and pieces on the surface, and taking off.  Repeat x5 and I was getting a little bored.  The gameplay is interesting, but repetitive.  An autopilot to selected planet would help, as would an auto-land feature.  The ""no loading"" feature is amazing, as the game more or less seamlessly transitions from deep space to planetary atmosphere.  Atmospheric landing was interesting; I loved the shaking of the spacecraft during atmospheric descent.  The game leaves you quite on your own at the beginning, and some tips in the tutorial would be welcome.  (Hint: follow all indicators on your screen, and land as close to them as possible.)  I will probably leave the game for a few weeks and revisit, just to give myself a fresh chance at it.  Overall, not recommended from me at this time, but the game has real potential and needs to flesh out the universe for it really to come into its own.2017-02: back to playing with it and I am reminded that the music is fantastic. I bought the soundtrack to support the developer.  Finding the alien NPCs to be a bit comedic as they race at full tilt around asteroid surfaces shooting blasters at you.  I'm sure this will be fleshed out in future versions.  Still find the game slightly tedious and the planet surfaces boring, but I'll make my way to one of the new gravity bikes and try those out, if I can.  All gripes aside, floating in space listening to the excellent music is worth a few bucks.  Graphics are nothing to write home about, but somehow, it's easy to overlook them while you float in space.  I'd recommend at a discounted price, or for anyone who just loves to tool around in a free world-universe (that doesn't really have that much going on) while listening to great music.  Will continue to explore."
